  "prompt": "Can an IAS officer create a secret agency within the district?",
  "response": "No, an IAS (Indian Administrative Service) officer does not have the authority to create a secret agency within a district or any other jurisdiction. The formation of agencies or departments typically requires approval from higher authorities, such as the state or central government, and must adhere to established laws and regulations. \n\nThe responsibilities of an IAS officer primarily involve administration, policy implementation, and governance within the district, rather than establishing independent agencies. Any initiative that involves sensitive or security-related tasks would generally fall under the purview of designated law enforcement or intelligence agencies, which operate under specific legal frameworks and oversight.",
